<subSubSection pageId="356" pageNumber="357" type="reference_group">
<paragraph pageId="356" pageNumber="357">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Casey" authorityYear="1918" class="Hexapoda" family="Carabidae" genus="Bembidion" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Coleoptera" pageId="356" pageNumber="357" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="levettei">Bembidion levettei</taxonomicName>
Casey, 1918: 9. Type locality: 
<normalizedToken originalValue="«Colorado»">&quot;Colorado&quot;</normalizedToken>
(original citation). Lectotype (♂), designated by Lindroth (1975: 114), in USNM [# 36793]. Etymology. The specific name was proposed for Dr. Gilbert M. Levette who worked as assistant for the Indiana Geological Survey in Indianapolis. Levette collected natural history specimens, particularly shells, beetles, reptiles and amphibians. His collection of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Linnaeus" authorityYear="1758" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Malvaceae" genus="Coleoptera" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="" order="Malvales" pageId="356" pageNumber="357" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">Coleoptera</taxonomicName>
was purchased by Thomas Casey in 1890.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="356" pageNumber="357" type="distribution">
<paragraph pageId="356" pageNumber="357">Distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="356" pageNumber="357">
The range of this subspecies extends from central Washington to southwestern Alberta, south to northern New Mexico [see Maddison 1993: Fig. 272]. One specimen labeled 
<normalizedToken originalValue="“Cal.”">&quot;Cal.&quot;</normalizedToken>
is known (Maddison 1993: 191). Fossil remnants from a Plio-Pleistocene sequence have been unearthed in northwestern Greenland and Banks Island (
<normalizedToken originalValue="Böcher">Boecher</normalizedToken>
1995: 23).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
